### PHP GET and POST

PHP uses `$_GET` and `$_POST` superglobals to collect form data.

### GET Method

Data is appended to the URL as query parameters.

```php
<?php
// URL: welcome.php?name=John&age=25
if (isset($_GET["name"])) {
    $name = $_GET["name"];
    echo "Welcome, $name!";
}

if (isset($_GET["age"])) {
    echo "You are " . $_GET["age"] . " years old.";
}
?>
```

### POST Method

Data is sent in the HTTP request body, not visible in the URL.

```php
<?php
if ($_SERVER["REQUEST_METHOD"] == "POST") {
    $username = $_POST["username"];
    $password = $_POST["password"];
    // Process login...
}
?>
```

### When to Use Each

| Use GET when... | Use POST when... |
|-----------------|------------------|
| Retrieving data | Sending sensitive data |
| Search queries | Updating databases |
| Bookmarkable pages | File uploads |
| Idempotent operations | Large data submissions |

### Self-submitting Form

```php
<form method="post" action="<?php echo htmlspecialchars($_SERVER["PHP_SELF"]); ?>">
    <input type="text" name="search" placeholder="Search...">
    <input type="submit">
</form>
```

> **Key Point:** Always check `isset()` before accessing `$_GET` or `$_POST` to avoid undefined array key warnings.
